&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; the last block that you reference has small print that says &quot;Compare the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; hypothesis to the experiment&#39;s conclusion&quot;.  Which of course you can&#39;t do
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; unless you already visited the hypothesis block and have a hypothesis to
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; which to compare.  That in turn has small print which says &quot;predict the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; outcome of the problem&quot;, which of course you can&#39;t do either unless you&#39;ve
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; already visited the earlier block of Purpose (&quot;state the problem&quot;).
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; I don&#39;t think it&#39;s helpful to deny good evidence, whether it is good
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; evidence from someone claiming to have detected spirits, or whether it is
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; good evidence from someone claiming that people can mistake noise for speech
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; or random radio tunings for spirit control.  That&#39;s why the scientific
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; method is valuable: it keeps both the skeptic and the believer real.
